post_text: Our school continues to have zero positive COVID-19 cases. This is true of the jr-sr high school as well. I do not believe this is an accident - I believe it is a direct effect of: our students’ excellent compliance to our reopening plan, the efforts of Nurse Beth and Nurse Heather, the dedication of our staff, especially our custodial staff including Mrs. Fox who is wiping down surfaces all day long, and our parents and guardians that are keeping kids home if they show symptoms that could possibly indicate COVID. Prevention can feel boring because we can’t know if the worst could have happened if we were not being proactive, but seeing our community stay healthy tells me it is worth the effort. We hope our team rests up over this long weekend, and then we will be back to teaching students and doing our best to keep them healthy and safe!

post_text: Kindergarten recess is always loads of fun, but yesterday we had a special guest! The kindegarteners found a toad near the playground. That can be tricky - will they squeeze it too tight, will an over-excited kid be too rough with it? No! Rose handled it like a professional toad-wrangler, all these students were so excited to see it, and then she took it to a safer place to release it. Near the playground is a bit too precarious a place to live for an amphibian.

post_text: Reorganization of the Library began over the summer and has fallen in the hands of our new librarian Mrs. Eisenhour. Books are being sorted by letters A-Z: each letter correlating with a lexile range. Shoulders deep in a sea of books, she has big plans. "I want it to be a happy place. I want it to be a place they want to come to," she says. Apart from sorting books, she's coming up with ways to make the library exciting. One of her initiatives is "Love it or Leave it". Students will pick out a mystery book wrapped in a brown paper bag. Not knowing what book it is, students are asked to participate in 30 minutes of reading in class, then decide if they "Love it or Leave it." Mrs. Eisenhour visits each classroom during their Library special while the Library continues to under go vast transformation.

post_text: We turn over the lunch room 5 times each day. Each new group of students sits down at tables that have been cleaned. Since groups are coming in every 20 minutes, it can be tricky to know which tables need wiped down, and which ones have already been wiped down. Sometimes it is easy when there are ketchup smears you can see, but coronavirus germs are invisible. Today we started using colored cards to tell us what’s been cleaned, and which tables have had a student sit there and then need wiped down. Our students’ safety is our top priority! #BestSmallSchoolInTheState

post_text:
Considerations outlined within the Eminence Community School Corporation plan are intended to provide guidance for preparing school operations under the current pandemic environment. This document follows the guidelines and recommendations from Indiana’s Considerations for Learning and Safe Schools (IN-CLASS). The conditions, current medical landscape, and growing body of knowledge surrounding COVID-19 continue to evolve. This reality presents challenges to planning, preparing, and guiding school operations. Not all districts and schools will look the same. Therefore, expect document revisions accordingly.
Eminence Community School Corporation will continue to review the CDC’s Decision Tree, the CDC Considerations for Schools, and the CDC’s Community Mitigation Strategies. Eminence will work closely with the Morgan County Department of Health as plans are put into place for reopening. Eminence will also work with the Morgan County Department of Health when there is a confirmed case.

Students will walk into their classrooms and have a pile of the necessary supplies on their desks. Due to concerns about germs, we will be minimizing shared supplies. We hope that providing the school supplies will support our families in this tricky time, and allow them to focus on other things rather than chasing down erasers and glue sticks. [ 94 more words ]

Eminence Community Schools is proud to announce our rescheduled commencement celebration. Our commencement, which would have happened in May, had been postponed due to the governor's orders that schools close through June 30th. As we prioritize the safety of our community and the importance of this event for our Seniors and their families, we have settled on a plan that fits within the states stage 4.5 guidelines and has the support of Morgan County Public Health Preparedness and Response Coordinator, Steve Lyday. STAFF SPOTLIGHT!
Meet Julie Shuler, our guidance secretary! Mrs. Shuler has worked here for 15 years. When her duaghter started kindergarten at Eminence, she started as a substitute teacher, then became the AEP coordinator, the K-12 secretary, and now resides as the guidance secretary. She enjoys being part of a small community and the seeing the students' beautiful smiling faces each day. "We are a true family here at Eminence...the staff here at Eminence can't be beat."

STAFF SPOTLIGHT!
Meet Hannah Sightes, our Guidance Counselor! Ms. Sightes has been a part of the Eminence team for two years. Her favorite thing about being a part of the Eminence staff is working in a tight-knit community. "Everyone here cares about our students and strives to make Eminence the absolute best, most fun place to be. I grew up loving school and loving to learn. I enjoy working with kids and want to make a difference in their lives."

post_text: We are very proud to announce that we recently received word from the State of Indiana Department of Education about our application to be recognized as a STEM certified school. When they reviewed the evidence of what we've done over the past couple years, they scored us at the highest level of Innovating (75 out of a possible 78 points!) We qualify for a state visit where representatives come out and see for themselves all the ways we enhance the education of our students with Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math! It is a GREAT day to be an Eel! #BestSmallSchoolInTheState

post_text: Luke and AJ won our 2nd Annual STEMinence VEX IQ Blended Tournament, and by doing so, have qualified for the state tournament at Lucas Oil Stadium! They also won the Excellence Award and Skills Championship. This makes two tournaments in a row they have won. There are more than 1200 elementary school robotics teams in the state vying for the 200 spots in this tournament, and our Eels got not one, but have qualified 3 times! Now they turn their attention to winning state, and possibly earning an invitation to the VEX World Championship.

post_text: MaKenna and Lynnsey won the tournament and are going to state!
shared_text:
Eminence Elementary School
January 31 at 11:28 AM ·

Wish our Eminence Elementary Robotics some luck for tomorrow - Ultimate Fix (Destiny, Gavin, and Wyatt) and Burnin' Mac and Cheese (MaKenna and Lynnsey) are heading all the way to Scottsburg early tomorrow morning to try to bring home their own state tournament* qualifications. They were close last week, only falling short to other Eminence teams. Luke and AJ have already qualified, so they aren't competing this time. Hopefully all of our teams move on to state thanks to this tournament, but if not, we'll have one more chance at our February 8th home tournament in the multi.

*There are more than 1200 elementary robotics teams in the state, and only 200 spots at the state tournament at Lucas Oil Stadium. Earning a spot is the goal of most of those teams, and one of our teams already qualified 3 separate times. If a school our size qualified 2 or even all 3 teams - that's incredible!

Earning a spot is the goal of most of those teams, and one of our teams already qualified 3 separate times. If a school our size qualified 2 or even all 3 teams - that's incredible!
text:
Wish our Eminence Elementary Robotics some luck for tomorrow - Ultimate Fix (Destiny, Gavin, and Wyatt) and Burnin' Mac and Cheese (MaKenna and Lynnsey) are heading all the way to Scottsburg early tomorrow morning to try to bring home their own state tournament* qualifications. They were close last week, only falling short to other Eminence teams. Luke and AJ have already qualified, so they aren't competing this time. Hopefully all of our teams move on to state thanks to this tournament, but if not, we'll have one more chance at our February 8th home tournament in the multi.

*There are more than 1200 elementary robotics teams in the state, and only 200 spots at the state tournament at Lucas Oil Stadium. Earning a spot is the goal of most of those teams, and one of our teams already qualified 3 separate times. If a school our size qualified 2 or even all 3 teams - that's incredible!

shared_text:
Eminence Guidance
January 9 at 5:27 PM ·

Day 2 of 3 of the ADAP Program! Students are learning so much valuable information!

All 9th grade students are participating in a 3 day program called the Adolescent Depression Awareness Program (ADAP). ADAP delivers the core message that depression and bipolar disorder are treatable medical illnesses and that concerned individuals should seek help. Through this work, ADAP aims to increase awareness and decrease stigma about mood disorders in young people while stressing the need for evaluation and treatment.
